POST http://localhost:8081/api/documents
Content-Type: multipart/form-data; boundary=WebAppBoundary

--WebAppBoundary
Content-Disposition: form-data; name="file"; filename="test.txt"
Content-Type: text/plain

The history of artificial intelligence began in antiquity, with myths, stories and rumors of artificial beings endowed with intelligence or consciousness by master craftsmen. The seeds of modern AI were planted by philosophers who attempted to describe the process of human thinking as the mechanical manipulation of symbols. This work culminated in the invention of the programmable digital computer in the 1940s, a machine based on the abstract essence of mathematical reasoning.

In the 1950s, researchers began to seriously pursue the idea that machines could be made to simulate all aspects of human intelligence. The field of AI research was founded at a workshop held on the campus of Dartmouth College in 1956. Attendees became the leaders of AI research for decades, and many predicted that a machine as intelligent as a human would exist within a generation.

Progress slowed considerably during periods now called AI winters, when funding and interest in artificial intelligence research declined. However, the field experienced a resurgence following advances in machine learning, particularly deep learning techniques that leverage large neural networks trained on massive datasets.

Modern applications of artificial intelligence span numerous domains including natural language processing, computer vision, robotics, and autonomous systems. Large language models trained on vast corpora of text have demonstrated remarkable capabilities in understanding and generating human language, enabling applications such as conversational assistants, automated content generation, and code completion tools.

Retrieval augmented generation has emerged as an important technique for grounding large language model outputs in factual, verifiable information. By combining the generative capabilities of language models with retrieval systems that fetch relevant documents from a knowledge base, RAG systems can produce more accurate and contextually appropriate responses while reducing the tendency of language models to generate plausible sounding but factually incorrect information.

